{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"It's a simple idea about nature."},{"time":2000,"text":"I want to say a word for nature"},{"time":4000,"text":"because we haven't talked that much about it the last couple days."},{"time":6000,"text":"I want to say a word for the soil and the bees and the plants and the animals,"},{"time":11000,"text":"and tell you about a tool, a very simple tool that I have found."},{"time":16000,"text":"Although it's really nothing more than a literary conceit; it's not a technology."},{"time":21000,"text":"It's very powerful for, I think, changing our relationship to the natural world"},{"time":27000,"text":"and to the other species on whom we depend."},{"time":30000,"text":"And that tool is very simply, as Chris suggested,"},{"time":33000,"text":"looking at us and the world from the plants' or the animals' point of view."},{"time":38000,"text":"It's not my idea, other people have hit on it,"},{"time":42000,"text":"but I've tried to take it to some new places."}]},{"cues":[{"time":46000,"text":"Let me tell you where I got it."},{"time":48000,"text":"Like a lot of my ideas, like a lot of the tools I use,"},{"time":51000,"text":"I found it in the garden; I'm a very devoted gardener."},{"time":55000,"text":"And there was a day about seven years ago: I was planting potatoes,"},{"time":59000,"text":"it was the first week of May --"},{"time":61000,"text":"this is New England, when the apple trees are just vibrating with bloom;"},{"time":66000,"text":"they're just white clouds above."},{"time":68000,"text":"I was here, planting my chunks,"},{"time":71000,"text":"cutting up potatoes and planting it,"},{"time":73000,"text":"and the bees were working on this tree;"},{"time":76000,"text":"bumblebees, just making this thing vibrate."}]},{"cues":[{"time":78000,"text":"And one of the things I really like about gardening"},{"time":81000,"text":"is that it doesn't take all your concentration,"},{"time":84000,"text":"you really can't get hurt -- it's not like woodworking --"},{"time":86000,"text":"and you have plenty of kind of mental space for speculation."},{"time":90000,"text":"And the question I asked myself that afternoon in the garden,"},{"time":94000,"text":"working alongside that bumblebee,"},{"time":97000,"text":"was: what did I and that bumblebee have in common?"},{"time":101000,"text":"How was our role in this garden similar and different?"},{"time":105000,"text":"And I realized we actually had quite a bit in common:"},{"time":107000,"text":"both of us were disseminating the genes of one species and not another,"},{"time":113000,"text":"and both of us -- probably, if I can imagine the bee's point of view --"},{"time":118000,"text":"thought we were calling the shots."},{"time":120000,"text":"I had decided what kind of potato I wanted to plant --"},{"time":124000,"text":"I had picked my Yukon Gold or Yellow Finn, or whatever it was --"},{"time":128000,"text":"and I had summoned those genes from a seed catalog across the country,"},{"time":133000,"text":"brought it, and I was planting it."},{"time":135000,"text":"And that bee, no doubt, assumed that it had decided,"},{"time":139000,"text":"\"I'm going for that apple tree, I'm going for that blossom,"},{"time":142000,"text":"I'm going to get the nectar and I'm going to leave.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":145000,"text":"We have a grammar that suggests that's who we are;"},{"time":150000,"text":"that we are sovereign subjects in nature, the bee as well as me."},{"time":155000,"text":"I plant the potatoes, I weed the garden, I domesticate the species."},{"time":161000,"text":"But that day, it occurred to me:"},{"time":163000,"text":"what if that grammar is nothing more than a self-serving conceit?"},{"time":166000,"text":"Because, of course, the bee thinks he's in charge or she's in charge,"},{"time":170000,"text":"but we know better."},{"time":172000,"text":"We know that what's going on between the bee and that flower"},{"time":176000,"text":"is that bee has been cleverly manipulated by that flower."},{"time":180000,"text":"And when I say manipulated, I'm talking about in a Darwinian sense, right?"},{"time":183000,"text":"I mean it has evolved a very specific set of traits --"},{"time":186000,"text":"color, scent, flavor, pattern -- that has lured that bee in."},{"time":191000,"text":"And the bee has been cleverly fooled into taking the nectar,"},{"time":195000,"text":"and also picking up some powder on its leg,"},{"time":198000,"text":"and going off to the next blossom."},{"time":200000,"text":"The bee is not calling the shots."},{"time":203000,"text":"And I realized then, I wasn't either."}]},{"cues":[{"time":205000,"text":"I had been seduced by that potato and not another"},{"time":208000,"text":"into planting its -- into spreading its genes, giving it a little bit more habitat."},{"time":213000,"text":"And that's when I got the idea, which was, \"Well, what would happen"},{"time":217000,"text":"if we kind of looked at us from this point of view of these other species who are working on us?\""},{"time":220000,"text":"And agriculture suddenly appeared to me not as an invention, not as a human technology,"},{"time":225000,"text":"but as a co-evolutionary development"},{"time":227000,"text":"in which a group of very clever species, mostly edible grasses, had exploited us,"},{"time":233000,"text":"figured out how to get us to basically deforest the world."},{"time":238000,"text":"The competition of grasses, right?"},{"time":241000,"text":"And suddenly everything looked different."},{"time":243000,"text":"And suddenly mowing the lawn that day was a completely different experience."}]},{"cues":[{"time":247000,"text":"I had thought always -- and in fact, had written this in my first book;"},{"time":250000,"text":"this was a book about gardening --"},{"time":251000,"text":"that lawns were nature under culture's boot,"},{"time":256000,"text":"that they were totalitarian landscapes,"},{"time":258000,"text":"and that when we mowed them we were cruelly suppressing the species"},{"time":262000,"text":"and never letting it set seed or die or have sex."},{"time":266000,"text":"And that's what the lawn was."},{"time":268000,"text":"But then I realized, \"No, this is exactly what the grasses want us to do."},{"time":272000,"text":"I'm a dupe. I'm a dupe of the lawns, whose goal in life is to outcompete the trees,"},{"time":279000,"text":"who they compete with for sunlight.\""},{"time":282000,"text":"And so by getting us to mow the lawn, we keep the trees from coming back,"},{"time":286000,"text":"which in New England happens very, very quickly."}]},{"cues":[{"time":289000,"text":"So I started looking at things this way"},{"time":292000,"text":"and wrote a whole book about it called \"The Botany of Desire.\""},{"time":294000,"text":"And I realized that in the same way you can look at a flower"},{"time":298000,"text":"and deduce all sorts of interesting things about the taste and the desires of bees --"},{"time":303000,"text":"that they like sweetness, that they like this color and not that color, that they like symmetry --"},{"time":309000,"text":"what could we find out about ourselves by doing the same thing?"},{"time":312000,"text":"That a certain kind of potato, a certain kind of drug,"},{"time":315000,"text":"a sativa-indica Cannabis cross has something to say about us."},{"time":321000,"text":"And that, wouldn't this be kind of an interesting way to look at the world?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":326000,"text":"Now, the test of any idea -- I said it was a literary conceit --"},{"time":330000,"text":"is what does it get us?"},{"time":333000,"text":"And when you're talking about nature, which is really my subject as a writer,"},{"time":337000,"text":"how does it meet the Aldo Leopold test?"},{"time":340000,"text":"Which is, does it make us better citizens of the biotic community?"},{"time":344000,"text":"Get us to do things that leads to the support and perpetuation of the biota,"},{"time":351000,"text":"rather than its destruction?"},{"time":352000,"text":"And I would submit that this idea does this."},{"time":354000,"text":"So, let me go through what you gain when you look at the world this way,"},{"time":357000,"text":"besides some entertaining insights about human desire."}]},{"cues":[{"time":362000,"text":"As an intellectual matter, looking at the world from other species' points of view"},{"time":369000,"text":"helps us deal with this weird anomaly,"},{"time":372000,"text":"which is -- and this is in the realm of intellectual history --"},{"time":376000,"text":"which is that we have this Darwinian revolution 150 years ago ..."},{"time":381000,"text":"Ugh. Mini-Me. (Laughter)"},{"time":386000,"text":"We have this intellectual, this Darwinian revolution in which, thanks to Darwin,"},{"time":392000,"text":"we figured out we are just one species among many;"},{"time":394000,"text":"evolution is working on us the same way it's working on all the others;"},{"time":398000,"text":"we are acted upon as well as acting;"},{"time":400000,"text":"we are really in the fiber, the fabric of life."},{"time":404000,"text":"But the weird thing is, we have not absorbed this lesson 150 years later;"},{"time":408000,"text":"none of us really believes this."},{"time":410000,"text":"We are still Cartesians -- the children of Descartes --"},{"time":415000,"text":"who believe that subjectivity, consciousness, sets us apart;"},{"time":420000,"text":"that the world is divided into subjects and objects;"},{"time":423000,"text":"that there is nature on one side, culture on another."},{"time":426000,"text":"As soon as you start seeing things from the plant's point of view or the animal's point of view,"},{"time":431000,"text":"you realize that the real literary conceit is that --"},{"time":435000,"text":"is the idea that nature is opposed to culture,"},{"time":439000,"text":"the idea that consciousness is everything --"},{"time":443000,"text":"and that's another very important thing it does."}]},{"cues":[{"time":446000,"text":"Looking at the world from other species' points of view"},{"time":449000,"text":"is a cure for the disease of human self-importance."},{"time":453000,"text":"You suddenly realize that consciousness --"},{"time":458000,"text":"which we value and we consider"},{"time":462000,"text":"the crowning achievement of nature,"},{"time":464000,"text":"human consciousness -- is really just another set of tools for getting along in the world."},{"time":469000,"text":"And it's kind of natural that we would think it was the best tool."},{"time":473000,"text":"But, you know, there's a comedian who said,"},{"time":475000,"text":"\"Well, who's telling me that consciousness is so good and so important?"},{"time":479000,"text":"Well, consciousness.\""},{"time":481000,"text":"So when you look at the plants, you realize that there are other tools"},{"time":485000,"text":"and they're just as interesting."}]},{"cues":[{"time":487000,"text":"I'll give you two examples, also from the garden:"},{"time":491000,"text":"lima beans. You know what a lima bean does when it's attacked by spider mites?"},{"time":496000,"text":"It releases this volatile chemical that goes out into the world"},{"time":499000,"text":"and summons another species of mite"},{"time":502000,"text":"that comes in and attacks the spider mite, defending the lima bean."},{"time":506000,"text":"So what plants have -- while we have consciousness, tool making, language,"},{"time":512000,"text":"they have biochemistry."},{"time":514000,"text":"And they have perfected that to a degree far beyond what we can imagine."},{"time":519000,"text":"Their complexity, their sophistication, is something to really marvel at,"},{"time":524000,"text":"and I think it's really the scandal of the Human Genome Project."},{"time":526000,"text":"You know, we went into it thinking, 40,000 or 50,000 human genes"},{"time":531000,"text":"and we came out with only 23,000."},{"time":535000,"text":"Just to give you grounds for comparison, rice: 35,000 genes."},{"time":543000,"text":"So who's the more sophisticated species?"},{"time":546000,"text":"Well, we're all equally sophisticated."},{"time":547000,"text":"We've been evolving just as long,"},{"time":550000,"text":"just along different paths."},{"time":553000,"text":"So, cure for self-importance, way to sort of make us feel the Darwinian idea."},{"time":561000,"text":"And that's really what I do as a writer, as a storyteller,"},{"time":564000,"text":"is try to make people feel what we know and tell stories that actually"},{"time":571000,"text":"help us think ecologically."}]},{"cues":[{"time":572000,"text":"Now, the other use of this is practical."},{"time":574000,"text":"And I'm going to take you to a farm right now,"},{"time":576000,"text":"because I used this idea to develop my understanding of the food system"},{"time":580000,"text":"and what I learned, in fact, is that we are all, now, being manipulated by corn."},{"time":585000,"text":"And the talk you heard about ethanol earlier today,"},{"time":590000,"text":"to me, is the final triumph of corn over good sense. (Laughter) (Applause)"},{"time":595000,"text":"It is part of corn's scheme for world domination."},{"time":603000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":604000,"text":"And you will see, the amount of corn planted this year will be up dramatically from last year"},{"time":608000,"text":"and there will be that much more habitat"},{"time":610000,"text":"because we've decided ethanol is going to help us."}]},{"cues":[{"time":612000,"text":"So it helped me understand industrial agriculture,"},{"time":616000,"text":"which of course is a Cartesian system."},{"time":618000,"text":"It's based on this idea that we bend other species to our will"},{"time":621000,"text":"and that we are in charge, and that we create these factories"},{"time":624000,"text":"and we have these technological inputs and we get the food out of it"},{"time":627000,"text":"or the fuel or whatever we want."},{"time":630000,"text":"Let me take you to a very different kind of farm."}]},{"cues":[{"time":632000,"text":"This is a farm in the Shenandoah Valley of Virginia."},{"time":635000,"text":"I went looking for a farm where these ideas"},{"time":638000,"text":"about looking at things from the species' point of view are actually implemented,"},{"time":642000,"text":"and I found it in a man. The farmer's name is Joel Salatin."},{"time":644000,"text":"And I spent a week as an apprentice on his farm,"},{"time":647000,"text":"and I took away from this some of the most hopeful news about our relationship to nature"},{"time":653000,"text":"that I've ever come across in 25 years of writing about nature."},{"time":656000,"text":"And that is this:"},{"time":657000,"text":"the farm is called Polyface, which means ..."},{"time":660000,"text":"the idea is he's got six different species of animals, as well as some plants,"},{"time":664000,"text":"growing in this very elaborate symbiotic arrangement."}]},{"cues":[{"time":667000,"text":"It's permaculture, those of you who know a little bit about this,"},{"time":669000,"text":"such that the cows and the pigs and the sheep and the turkeys and the ..."},{"time":677000,"text":"what else does he have?"},{"time":679000,"text":"All the six different species -- rabbits, actually --"},{"time":681000,"text":"are all performing ecological services for one another,"},{"time":684000,"text":"such that the manure of one is the lunch for the other"},{"time":687000,"text":"and they take care of pests for one another."},{"time":689000,"text":"It's a very elaborate and beautiful dance,"},{"time":692000,"text":"but I'm going to just give you a close-up on one piece of it,"},{"time":695000,"text":"and that is the relationship between his cattle and his chickens, his laying hens."},{"time":701000,"text":"And I'll show you, if you take this approach, what you get, OK?"},{"time":706000,"text":"And this is a lot more than growing food, as you'll see;"},{"time":708000,"text":"this is a different way to think about nature"},{"time":710000,"text":"and a way to get away from the zero-sum notion,"},{"time":714000,"text":"the Cartesian idea that either nature's winning or we're winning,"},{"time":717000,"text":"and that for us to get what we want, nature is diminished."}]},{"cues":[{"time":721000,"text":"So, one day, cattle in a pen."},{"time":723000,"text":"The only technology involved here is this cheap electric fencing:"},{"time":726000,"text":"relatively new, hooked to a car battery;"},{"time":728000,"text":"even I could carry a quarter-acre paddock, set it up in 15 minutes."},{"time":732000,"text":"Cows graze one day. They move, OK?"},{"time":736000,"text":"They graze everything down, intensive grazing."},{"time":738000,"text":"He waits three days,"},{"time":740000,"text":"and then we towed in something called the Eggmobile."},{"time":743000,"text":"The Eggmobile is a very rickety contraption --"},{"time":746000,"text":"it looks like a prairie schooner made out of boards --"},{"time":749000,"text":"but it houses 350 chickens."},{"time":751000,"text":"He tows this into the paddock three days later and opens the gangplank,"},{"time":757000,"text":"turns them down, and 350 hens come streaming down the gangplank --"},{"time":761000,"text":"clucking, gossiping as chickens will --"},{"time":763000,"text":"and they make a beeline for the cow patties."}]},{"cues":[{"time":768000,"text":"And what they're doing is very interesting:"},{"time":770000,"text":"they're digging through the cow patties"},{"time":772000,"text":"for the maggots, the grubs, the larvae of flies."},{"time":776000,"text":"And the reason he's waited three days"},{"time":778000,"text":"is because he knows that on the fourth day or the fifth day, those larvae will hatch"},{"time":783000,"text":"and he'll have a huge fly problem."},{"time":785000,"text":"But he waits that long to grow them as big and juicy and tasty as he can"},{"time":791000,"text":"because they are the chickens' favorite form of protein."}]},{"cues":[{"time":794000,"text":"So the chickens do their kind of little breakdance"},{"time":796000,"text":"and they're pushing around the manure to get at the grubs,"},{"time":800000,"text":"and in the process they're spreading the manure out."},{"time":803000,"text":"Very useful second ecosystem service."},{"time":807000,"text":"And third, while they're in this paddock"},{"time":810000,"text":"they are, of course, defecating madly"},{"time":813000,"text":"and their very nitrogenous manure is fertilizing this field."},{"time":819000,"text":"They then move out to the next one,"},{"time":821000,"text":"and in the course of just a few weeks, the grass just enters this blaze of growth."},{"time":829000,"text":"And within four or five weeks, he can do it again."},{"time":831000,"text":"He can graze again, he can cut, he can bring in another species,"},{"time":834000,"text":"like the lambs, or he can make hay for the winter."}]},{"cues":[{"time":839000,"text":"Now, I want you to just look really close up onto what's happened there."},{"time":843000,"text":"So, it's a very productive system."},{"time":844000,"text":"And what I need to tell you is that on 100 acres"},{"time":846000,"text":"he gets 40,000 pounds of beef; 30,000 pounds of pork; 25,000 dozen eggs;"},{"time":851000,"text":"20,000 broilers; 1,000 turkeys; 1,000 rabbits --"},{"time":854000,"text":"an immense amount of food."}]},{"cues":[{"time":856000,"text":"You know, you hear, \"Can organic feed the world?\""},{"time":858000,"text":"Well, look how much food you can produce on 100 acres if you do this kind of ..."},{"time":863000,"text":"again, give each species what it wants,"},{"time":866000,"text":"let it realize its desires, its physiological distinctiveness."},{"time":870000,"text":"Put that in play."}]},{"cues":[{"time":872000,"text":"But look at it from the point of view of the grass, now."},{"time":875000,"text":"What happens to the grass when you do this?"},{"time":877000,"text":"When a ruminant grazes grass, the grass is cut from this height to this height,"},{"time":883000,"text":"and it immediately does something very interesting."},{"time":885000,"text":"Any one of you who gardens knows that there is something called the root-shoot ratio,"},{"time":889000,"text":"and plants need to keep the root mass"},{"time":893000,"text":"in some rough balance with the leaf mass to be happy."},{"time":896000,"text":"So when they lose a lot of leaf mass, they shed roots;"},{"time":900000,"text":"they kind of cauterize them and the roots die."},{"time":903000,"text":"And the species in the soil go to work"},{"time":906000,"text":"basically chewing through those roots, decomposing them --"},{"time":910000,"text":"the earthworms, the fungi, the bacteria -- and the result is new soil."},{"time":916000,"text":"This is how soil is created."},{"time":919000,"text":"It's created from the bottom up."},{"time":920000,"text":"This is how the prairies were built,"},{"time":922000,"text":"the relationship between bison and grasses."}]},{"cues":[{"time":925000,"text":"And what I realized when I understood this --"},{"time":928000,"text":"and if you ask Joel Salatin what he is, he'll tell you he's not a chicken farmer,"},{"time":932000,"text":"he's not a sheep farmer, he's not a cattle rancher; he's a grass farmer,"},{"time":937000,"text":"because grass is really the keystone species of such a system --"},{"time":941000,"text":"is that, if you think about it, this completely contradicts the tragic idea of nature we hold in our heads,"},{"time":950000,"text":"which is that for us to get what we want, nature is diminished."},{"time":956000,"text":"More for us, less for nature."},{"time":958000,"text":"Here, all this food comes off this farm, and at the end of the season"},{"time":963000,"text":"there is actually more soil, more fertility and more biodiversity."}]},{"cues":[{"time":970000,"text":"It's a remarkably hopeful thing to do."},{"time":973000,"text":"There are a lot of farmers doing this today."},{"time":975000,"text":"This is well beyond organic agriculture,"},{"time":978000,"text":"which is still a Cartesian system, more or less."},{"time":981000,"text":"And what it tells you is that if you begin to take account of other species,"},{"time":987000,"text":"take account of the soil, that even with nothing more than this perspectival idea"},{"time":994000,"text":"-- because there is no technology involved here except for those fences,"},{"time":998000,"text":"which are so cheap they could be all over Africa in no time --"},{"time":1003000,"text":"that we can take the food we need from the Earth"},{"time":1007000,"text":"and actually heal the Earth in the process."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1012000,"text":"This is a way to reanimate the world,"},{"time":1014000,"text":"and that's what's so exciting about this perspective."},{"time":1016000,"text":"When we really begin to feel Darwin's insights in our bones,"},{"time":1020000,"text":"the things we can do with nothing more than these ideas"},{"time":1025000,"text":"are something to be very hopeful about."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1027000,"text":"Thank you very much."}]}]}